DBMS – B.Sc. CSIT 4th Semester – Simplified Unit-wise Syllabus
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Unit I: Introduction to DBMS

Definition and key advantages of DBMS

Roles: database users and admins

Database system architecture: three‑schema architecture and data independence

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Unit II: Data Modeling (ER Model)

ER diagram basics: entities, relationships, attributes, keys

Extending models: weak entities, inheritance, specialization/generalization

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Unit III: Relational Model & Constraints

Relational schema, tuples, relations, and integrity constraints

Update operations and handling constraint violations

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Unit IV: Relational Algebra & Calculus

Basic operators: SELECT, PROJECT, UNION, JOIN, DIVISION, etc.

Tuple relational calculus and domain relational calculus

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Unit V: SQL

DDL and DML: defining structures, data types, and constraints

Queries: SELECT (simple & complex), INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE

Views and advanced retrieval techniques

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Unit VI: Relational Database Design

Mapping ER-to-relational schemas

Functional dependencies and normalization:

1NF, 2NF, 3NF

BCNF, 4NF, relational decomposition properties

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Unit VII: Transaction Processing

Core concepts of transactions

ACID properties: Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, Durability

Schedule recoverability and serializability

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Unit VIII: Concurrency Control

Techniques for maintaining consistency in multi-user environments:

Two-phase locking

Timestamp ordering

Multiversion concurrency control

Optimistic validation and snapshot isolation

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Unit IX: Database Recovery Techniques

Methods to recover from failures:

Deferred update (No‑Undo/Redo)

Immediate update (Undo/Redo)

Shadow paging

Backup and restoration strategies for catastrophic failure

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Overview Table – Unit at a Glance
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Unit	Core Topics
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
I	DBMS fundamentals & architecture
II	ER modeling & data representation
III	Relational schemas & integrity constraints
IV	Relational algebra & logic-based querying
V	SQL—creation, manipulation, and querying
VI	Schema design & normalization processes
VII	Transaction theory & ACID properties
VIII	Concurrency control mechanisms
IX	Recovery techniques & backup strategies
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
